ğŸ“Œ Threat level: Very High (hard to detect).

3. Hacktivists âœŠ

Who they are:
Attackers driven by political, social, or ideological motives.

Motivation:

Protest

Public awareness

Political messages

Skills Level: Medium

Typical Attacks:

Website defacement

DDoS attacks

Data leaks (doxxing)

Real-world Groups:

Anonymous

LulzSec (historically)

Real-world Example:

DDoS attack on a government website during protests

ğŸ“Œ Threat level: Medium (high visibility, reputational damage).

4. Nation-State Actors ğŸŒ

Who they are:
Highly skilled attackers sponsored by governments.

Motivation:

Espionage

Cyber warfare

Intellectual property theft

Skills Level: Very High (APT groups)

Typical Attacks:

Zero-day exploits

Advanced Persistent Threats (APTs)

Supply chain attacks

Real-world Examples:

Stuxnet attack on Iranian nuclear facilities

SolarWinds supply-chain attack

Known APT Groups:

